answer:
By the Law of Sines in triangle $ABE,$
\[\frac{BE}{\sin (x + y)} = \frac{AE}{\sin B} \quad \Rightarrow \quad \sin (x + y) = \frac{BE \sin B}{AE}.\]By the Law of Sines in triangle $ADC,$
\[\frac{CD}{\sin (y + z)} = \frac{AD}{\sin C} \quad \Rightarrow \quad \sin (y + z) = \frac{CD \sin C}{AD}.\][asy]
unitsize (2 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E;

B = (0,0);
D = (1,0);
E = (2,0);
C = (3,0);
A = (2.5,1.5);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);
draw(A--E);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$E$", E, S);
label("$x$", A + (-0.75,-0.6));
label("$y$", A + (-0.35,-0.6));
label("$z$", A + (0,-0.5));
[/asy]

By the Law of Sines in triangle $ABD,$
\[\frac{BD}{\sin x} = \frac{AD}{\sin B} \quad \Rightarrow \quad \sin x = \frac{BD \sin B}{AD}.\]By the Law of Sines in triangle $AEC,$
\[\frac{CE}{\sin z} = \frac{AE}{\sin C} \quad \Rightarrow \quad \sin z = \frac{CE \sin C}{AE}.\]Hence,
\begin{align*}
\frac{\sin (x + y) \sin (y + z)}{\sin x \sin z} &= \frac{\frac{BE \sin B}{AE} \cdot \frac{CD \sin C}{AD}}{\frac{BD \sin B}{AD} \cdot \frac{CE \sin C}{AE}} \\
&= \frac{BE \cdot CD}{BD \cdot CE} \\
&= \frac{2BD \cdot 2CE}{BD \cdot CE} = \boxed{4}.
\end{align*}

By Pythagoras, the lengths $x,$ $\sqrt{16 - x^2},$ and 4 are the sides of a right triangle.  Similarly, $y,$ $\sqrt{25 -  y^2},$ and 5 are the sides of a right triangle, and $z,$ $\sqrt{36 - z^2},$ and 6 are the sides of a right triangle.  Stack these right triangles, as shown below.  Then $AE = x + y + z = 9$ and
\[DE = \sqrt{16 - x^2} + \sqrt{25 - y^2} + \sqrt{36 - z^2}.\][asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, P, Q, R, trans;

A = (0,0);
B = 4*dir(40);
C = B + 5*dir(60);
D = C + 6*dir(30);
E = (D.x,0);
P = (B.x,0);
Q = (C.x,B.y);
R = (D.x,C.y);
trans = (14,0);

draw(A--B--P--cycle);
draw(B--C--Q--cycle);
draw(C--D--R--cycle);
draw(P--E--R,dashed);

label("$x$", (A + P)/2, S, red);
label("$\sqrt{16 - x^2}$", (B + P)/2, dir(0), red);
label("$4$", (A + B)/2, NW, red);
label("$y$", (B + Q)/2, S, red);
label("$\sqrt{25 - y^2}$", (C + Q)/2, dir(0), red);
label("$5$", (B + C)/2, NW, red);
label("$z$", (C + R)/2, S, red);
label("$\sqrt{36 - z^2}$", (D + R)/2, dir(0), red);
label("$6$", (C + D)/2, NW, red);
label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, NW);
label("$C$", C, NW);
label("$D$", D, NE);
label("$E$", E, SE);

draw(shift(trans)*(A--B--C--D--E--cycle));
draw(shift(trans)*(A--D),dashed);

label("$A$", A + trans, SW);
label("$B$", B + trans, SE);
label("$C$", C + trans, NW);
label("$D$", D + trans, NE);
label("$E$", E + trans, SE);
label("$9$", (A + E)/2 + trans, S, red);
label("$\sqrt{16 - x^2} + \sqrt{25 - y^2} + \sqrt{36 - z^2}$", (D + E)/2 + trans, dir(0), red);
[/asy]

By the Triangle Inequality,
\[AD \le AB + BC + CD = 4 + 5 + 6 = 15.\]By Pythagoras on right triangle $ADE,$
\[9^2 + (\sqrt{16 - x^2} + \sqrt{25 - y^2} + \sqrt{36 - z^2})^2 = AD^2 \le 15^2,\]so $(\sqrt{16 - x^2} + \sqrt{25 - y^2} + \sqrt{36 - z^2})^2 \le 15^2 - 9^2 = 144.$  Hence,
\[\sqrt{16 - x^2} + \sqrt{25 - y^2} + \sqrt{36 - z^2} \le 12.\]Equality occurs when $x = \frac{12}{5},$ $y = 3,$ and $z = \frac{18}{5}.$  (Note that this corresponds to the case where $A,$ $B,$ $C,$ and $D$ are collinear.)  Thus, the maximum value we seek is $\boxed{12}.$

Let $h = AD.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (3,11);
B = (0,0);
D = (3,0);
C = (20,0);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$3$", (B + D)/2, S);
label("$17$", (C + D)/2, S);
label("$h$", (A + D)/2, E);
[/asy]

Then $\tan \angle BAD = \frac{3}{h}$ and $\tan \angle CAD = \frac{17}{h},$ so
\begin{align*}
\tan A &= \tan (\angle BAD + \angle CAD) \\
&= \frac{\tan \angle BAD + \tan \angle CAD}{1 - \tan \angle BAD \cdot \tan \angle CAD} \\
&= \frac{\frac{3}{h} + \frac{17}{h}}{1 - \frac{3}{h} \cdot \frac{17}{h}} \\
&= \frac{20h}{h^2 - 51}.
\end{align*}Thus, $\frac{20h}{h^2 - 51} = \frac{22}{7}.$  This simplifies to
\[11h^2 - 70h - 561 = 0,\]which factors as $(h - 11)(11h + 51) = 0.$  Hence, $h = 11,$ and the area of triangle $ABC$ is $\frac{1}{2} \cdot 20 \cdot 11 = \boxed{110}.$

Let $a = \angle DAB = \frac{1}{2} \angle CAD.$  Since $\frac{AC}{AD} = \frac{2}{3},$ without loss of generality, we can assume $AC = 2$ and $AD = 3.$  Then by Pythagoras on right triangle $ACD,$ $CD = \sqrt{5}.$

